67
00:03:46,710 --> 00:03:50,245
 People who had bought paintings
          from Knoedler         

68
00:03:50,247 --> 00:03:51,780
      were coming forward,      

69
00:03:51,782 --> 00:03:54,249
     having their paintings     
      forensically tested.      

70
00:03:54,251 --> 00:03:57,886
     And soon former federal    
   prosecutor Jason Hernandez   

71
00:03:57,888 --> 00:03:59,304
     and U.S. investigators     

72
00:03:59,306 --> 00:04:04,059
   will prove that a supplier   
provided the gallery with fakes,

73
00:04:04,061 --> 00:04:05,794
  sold for millions of dollars  

74
00:04:05,796 --> 00:04:09,181
      to some of America's      
     wealthiest collectors.     

75
00:04:09,183 --> 00:04:10,933
What those paintings represented

76
00:04:10,935 --> 00:04:13,185
         would have been        
    one of the greatest finds   

77
00:04:13,187 --> 00:04:17,072
         of the abstract        
 American Expressionist school. 

78
00:04:17,074 --> 00:04:20,492
 And these are paintings that go
  for millions of dollars each. 

79
00:04:20,494 --> 00:04:21,860
       Narrator: Knoedler,      

80
00:04:21,862 --> 00:04:25,330
    along with the gallery's    
     director Ann Freedman,     

81
00:04:25,332 --> 00:04:27,449
    say they've been fleeced    

82
00:04:27,451 --> 00:04:29,534
     just like their clients    

83
00:04:29,536 --> 00:04:34,589
    by a persuasive swindler    
     named Glafira Rosales.     

84
00:04:34,591 --> 00:04:36,925
       Glafira Rosales is       

85
00:04:36,927 --> 00:04:41,430
   an incredibly sophisticated  
           con artist.          

86
00:04:41,432 --> 00:04:43,498
    Narrator: Maria Konnikova   
          is the author         

87
00:04:43,500 --> 00:04:45,217
    of "The Confidence Game,"   

88
00:04:45,219 --> 00:04:47,352
    a book about fraudsters.    

89
00:04:47,354 --> 00:04:49,554
      She became intrigued      
         with the story         

90
00:04:49,556 --> 00:04:52,557
         when the rumors        
        started to erupt.       

91
00:04:52,559 --> 00:04:54,977
       What drew me to it       

92
00:04:54,979 --> 00:04:59,815
 wasn't just kind of the glamour
     of the art fraud world,    

93
00:04:59,817 --> 00:05:02,117
       but how it is that       
     incredibly smart people    

94
00:05:02,119 --> 00:05:04,987
 sometimes believe things that, 
         to an outsider,        

95
00:05:04,989 --> 00:05:07,656
      seem incredibly dumb.     

96
00:05:07,658 --> 00:05:09,658
       Narrator: According      
       to court documents,      

97
00:05:09,660 --> 00:05:11,493
         Glafira Rosales        
