109
00:05:39,323 --> 00:05:42,074
       to move to the real      
        city of dreams --       

110
00:05:42,076 --> 00:05:45,077
            New York.           

111
00:05:45,079 --> 00:05:48,730
   In 1986, Rosales is granted  
      permanent residence.      

112
00:05:48,732 --> 00:05:51,666
    She and Jose Bergantiños    
         have a daughter        

113
00:05:51,668 --> 00:05:55,370
      and buy a small house     
         in the suburbs.        

114
00:05:55,372 --> 00:05:58,507
      Rosales even fulfills     
    her childhood aspiration    

115
00:05:58,509 --> 00:06:01,426
        and opens a small       
     gallery business called    

116
00:06:01,428 --> 00:06:04,579
       "King's Fine Art."       

117
00:06:04,581 --> 00:06:07,382
 Konnikova: What Glafira Rosales
      told people was that      

118
00:06:07,384 --> 00:06:10,218
      she was from a family     
         that loved art,        

119
00:06:10,220 --> 00:06:14,639
  that had a lot of people come 
 to their house for art salons. 

120
00:06:14,641 --> 00:06:16,358
  And so from a very young age, 

121
00:06:16,360 --> 00:06:18,894
       she was fascinated       
         by this world.         

122
00:06:18,896 --> 00:06:20,946
    Narrator: Sometime later,   
          Rosales meets         

123
00:06:20,948 --> 00:06:24,649
       a well-liked figure      
   in the New York art scene,   

124
00:06:24,651 --> 00:06:29,104
 who happens to hold a position 
      at Knoedler Gallery.      

125
00:06:29,106 --> 00:06:30,605
  He offers to set up a meeting 

126
00:06:30,607 --> 00:06:35,494
  with the gallery's director,  
          Ann Freedman.         

127
00:06:35,496 --> 00:06:37,129
     Konnikova: Ann Freedman    
         was pretty new         

128
00:06:37,131 --> 00:06:38,663
  as the director of Knoedler.  

129
00:06:38,665 --> 00:06:40,832
   She'd been very successful   
        in her art career       

130
00:06:40,834 --> 00:06:44,970
      and someone who knows     
  how to sell things to people, 

131
00:06:44,972 --> 00:06:46,788
     which is what you need     
        in the art world.       

132
00:06:46,790 --> 00:06:49,257
    But now she really wanted   
         to make a mark         

133
00:06:49,259 --> 00:06:54,462
    as the female director of   
 this really prominent gallery. 

134
00:06:54,464 --> 00:06:55,964
Narrator: As luck would have it,

135
00:06:55,966 --> 00:07:01,069
       Rosales is looking       
     to make her mark, too.     

136
00:07:01,071 --> 00:07:02,571
           So in 1995,          

137
00:07:02,573 --> 00:07:04,739
        when 40 year-old        
         Glafira Rosales        

138
00:07:04,741 --> 00:07:07,859
 breezes into Knoedler & Company
         with a canvas,         

139
00:07:07,861 --> 00:07:10,195
        she's the epitome       
        of a well-dressed       

140
00:07:10,197 --> 00:07:13,865
   and cultivated art dealer.   

141
00:07:13,867 --> 00:07:16,985
        Lawyer Luke Nikas       
    represented Ann Freedman    

142
00:07:16,987 --> 00:07:20,839
      in what's been called     
 "the art trial of the century."

143
00:07:20,841 --> 00:07:23,375
        You have a woman        
        who's unassuming.       

144
00:07:23,377 --> 00:07:24,709
        She's not slick.        

145
00:07:24,711 --> 00:07:29,497
      She doesn't have this     
       well-planned story.      

146
00:07:29,499 --> 00:07:32,634
    She's got a relationship    
           with a man           

147
00:07:32,636 --> 00:07:35,470
   who inherited the painting   
        from his father,        

148
00:07:35,472 --> 00:07:38,140
     and he lived in Mexico.    

149
00:07:38,142 --> 00:07:41,693
  And he just wanted to get rid 
       of this collection.      

150
00:07:41,695 --> 00:07:44,496
    Narrator: Freedman leads    
        Rosales upstairs        

151
00:07:44,498 --> 00:07:47,165
    to a small drawing room.    

152
00:07:47,167 --> 00:07:49,701
       The painting's warm      
        peachy background       

153
00:07:49,703 --> 00:07:52,037
        with two ethereal       
         clouds of color        

154
00:07:52,039 --> 00:07:55,991
   is immediately recognizable  
  as the work of Mark Rothko -- 

155
00:07:55,993 --> 00:08:00,378
     a leading artist of the    
abstract-expressionist movement.

156
00:08:00,380 --> 00:08:03,248
       Rothko, along with       
        Jackson Pollock,        

157
00:08:03,250 --> 00:08:05,834
       Robert Motherwell,       
    and a few select others,    

158
00:08:05,836 --> 00:08:08,470
  were leaders of the abstract- 
     expressionist movement     

159
00:08:08,472 --> 00:08:12,373
    that emerged in New York    
        during the 1940s.       

160
00:08:12,375 --> 00:08:14,559
     That handful of artists    
         are the artists        

161
00:08:14,561 --> 00:08:18,680
    that are the most valued,   
  have the largest reputation,  

162
00:08:18,682 --> 00:08:22,984
       and in some cases,       
 also fetch the highest prices. 

163
00:08:22,986 --> 00:08:25,187
     Narrator: People don't     
     walk in off the street     

164
00:08:25,189 --> 00:08:26,938
       carrying a Rothko,       

165
00:08:26,940 --> 00:08:29,524
   and Ann Freedman knows it.   

166
00:08:29,526 --> 00:08:31,993
        When questioned,        
     Rosales spins her tale     

167
00:08:31,995 --> 00:08:35,280
  of growing up in a prominent  
   Catholic family in Mexico,   

168
00:08:35,282 --> 00:08:39,784
   surrounded by the crème de   
      la crème of society.      

169
00:08:39,786 --> 00:08:42,287
      That's where Glafira      
         came in contact        

170
00:08:42,289 --> 00:08:45,173
    with the heir to a secret   
        art collection --       

171
00:08:45,175 --> 00:08:49,577
    a man she refers to only    
           as "Mr. X."          

172
00:08:49,579 --> 00:08:50,929
     To begin, she would try    

173
00:08:50,931 --> 00:08:53,248
     to sell the collection     
      of a painter friend,      

174
00:08:53,250 --> 00:08:57,135
  someone whose confidentiality 
      she wanted to respect     

175
00:08:57,137 --> 00:09:01,890
     and so he became known     
            as Mr. X.           

176
00:09:01,892 --> 00:09:04,709
    Narrator: Mr. X's father    
        had been a patron       

177
00:09:04,711 --> 00:09:07,929
  of the abstract expressionist 
           art scene.           

178
00:09:07,931 --> 00:09:11,449
 He purchased artworks straight 
   from the artist's studios,   

179
00:09:11,451 --> 00:09:13,101
         paying in cash,        

180
00:09:13,103 --> 00:09:16,871
     so the assets and taxes    
      were never declared.      

181
00:09:16,873 --> 00:09:18,106
      According to Rosales,     

182
00:09:18,108 --> 00:09:22,994
  there's another family secret 
    that needs to be kept...    

183
00:09:22,996 --> 00:09:25,163
       Flam: This man was       
    married and had a family    

184
00:09:25,165 --> 00:09:28,783
 and he was a closet homosexual,
   and in Mexico, supposedly,   

185
00:09:28,785 --> 00:09:31,586
     it was dangerous to be     
   a homosexual at that time.   

186
00:09:31,588 --> 00:09:33,121
     And so the man had died    

187
00:09:33,123 --> 00:09:35,957
   and now his son was selling  
          the pictures,         

188
00:09:35,959 --> 00:09:39,060
     but he wanted to do it     
   as discreetly as possible.   

189
00:09:39,062 --> 00:09:42,430
 Narrator: But there's a bonus, 
       and it's alluring.       

190
00:09:42,432 --> 00:09:46,318
   This Rothko is just the tip  
         of the iceberg.        

191
00:09:46,320 --> 00:09:48,153
      Her secretive client      
        has a collection        

192
00:09:48,155 --> 00:09:52,607
   of previously unknown works  
      by Robert Motherwell,     

193
00:09:52,609 --> 00:09:58,146
       Willem de Kooning,       
   Jackson Pollock, and more.   

194
00:09:58,148 --> 00:10:03,752
   A Pollock painting in 2015   
     went for $200 million.     

195
00:10:03,754 --> 00:10:05,420
  Only a few years before that, 

196
00:10:05,422 --> 00:10:09,174
          a Rothko went         
    for $86 million dollars.    

197
00:10:09,176 --> 00:10:11,676
   They're really big numbers   
            involved.           

198
00:10:11,678 --> 00:10:14,346
  Narrator: This collection has 
     been hidden in storage     

199
00:10:14,348 --> 00:10:16,164
          for decades.          

200
00:10:16,166 --> 00:10:20,335
  But Rosales is not an expert  
    in abstract expressionism   

201
00:10:20,337 --> 00:10:25,023
       and her own gallery      
          is too small.         

202
00:10:25,025 --> 00:10:27,609
    It doesn't seem to matter   
    that few in the art world   

203
00:10:27,611 --> 00:10:30,195
    have heard of Rosales...    

204
00:10:30,197 --> 00:10:34,783
  This art is some of the most  
 valued art of the 20th century.

205
00:10:34,785 --> 00:10:38,036
  People paid tens of millions  
       of dollars for it,       

206
00:10:38,038 --> 00:10:42,123
 and we haven't had anything new
       in it for a while.       

207
00:10:42,125 --> 00:10:44,525
     Narrator: The gallery's    
   new director, Ann Freedman,  

208
00:10:44,527 --> 00:10:49,530
   is dazzled by the prospect   
          and profits.          

209
00:10:49,532 --> 00:10:51,583
 Up next on "American Greed"... 

